<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-497-554  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 497 554.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Educational Technology  May 1990 v30 n5 p32(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Alternate views: a case for case studies. (column)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Driscoll, Marcy P.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Case studies are plentiful and valuable as teaching strategies,but there is a need for case studies conducted for researchpurposes.andP;  Case studies conducted for research purposes mustconsider how to frame the research questions and define the caseto be studied, how to determine the relevant data to be collected,and how to analyze and present the data so that reasonableconclusions may result.andP;  The focus of such a case study,especially as it relates to instructional systems, determines howthe case to be studied is defined.andP;  Cases can be defined in termsof individuals, or in terms of techniques, methods, or technology.andO;Regardless of the focus, all case studies depend on multiplesources of evidence, and acquiring information may involve bothquantitative and qualitative measures.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Case StudyMethodsResearch DesignInformation Processing.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>